						<h2 class="mt-4">What is a game server?</h2>
						<p><strong>A game server is a computer that acts as a central authority to define the current state of a multiplayer game. The server sends constant updates to players providing a snapshot of all elements in the game.</strong></p>
						<p>To break that down, the server is where the game is being played <em>and</em> the referee.</p>
						<p>When you jump, your computer tells that to the server, and the server tells everyone else that you’re in the air.</p>
						<p>Game servers ensure that all players are seeing everything the same way. This is called a synchronised game state.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">What is a game state?</h3>
						<p>A game state is the true position of every object in the game world.</p>
						<p>In a multiplayer game, two players seeing different versions of the game can cause massive issues.</p>
						<p>When you duck behind cover in Counter-Strike or Call of Duty, only to be shot from an angle that is seemingly impossible, that’s the fault of the server desynchronising.</p>
						<p>A synchronised game state means that people can land headshots and play as intended, whereas a desynchronised game will have them sending angry emails instead.</p>
