						<p>There are three ways data can be sent to synchronise the game state.</p>
						<p> The first way that the state might be updated is by ‘sending state’.</p>
						<h4 class="mt-2">What is Sending State?</h4>
						<p>This is a high network traffic method of updating the various players of the game state.</p>
						<p>With every player sending constant updates, this design means that these games are more difficult to cheat in.
						 The second method for updating the state is less common for dedicated gaming servers and that is ‘sending input’.</p>
						<h4 class="mt-2">What is Sending Input?</h4>
						<p>Sending input works by only communicating what each player is attempting to do on their end, keeping file sizes smaller.</p>
						<p>This is easier to fake on your local computer, so these games are more susceptible to cheating.</p>
						<h4 class="mt-2">What is Client State?</h4>
						<p>A more common networking method is updated client state. Updated client state only sends information regarding the differences, which is less data than the entire game state.</p>
						<p>This works by rewinding to the state that the server sent and then tracking the difference between the two.</p>
						<p>All of these networking options work towards the same goal: ensuring all players have the correct version of the game state.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">Where are game servers?</h3>
						<p>A game server can be anywhere, including on your desk, if developers release server binaries.</p>
						<p>A server binary is an executable software that runs the game server. In essence, the server binary is the program that runs the game world, while your version of the multiplayer game sends information to it.</p>
						<p>Hosting games with a server binary on a computer in your home turns your computer into the host. </p>
						<p>Many games that release the binary and server software have long life spans and increased control given to the players. Team Fortress 2, Counter-Strike, and Minecraft are examples of popular games that give more control to players who host their own servers.</p>
						<p>If a developer does release the server binary, those can then be hosted from the home computer or a data centre, the key technical difference being speed and location.</p>
						<p>Some people use an old PC to run servers. But not everyone has the processing power or hardware required to run multiplayer computer games.</p>
