						<p>Another method, that also uses a home computer to run a server is called peer-to-peer. With peer-to-peer, the game assigns one player’s computer to also host the match, and runs the server in the background. Peer-to-peer hosting requires one of the networked devices to run both the video game, and the server.</p>
						<p>With peer-to-peer, anyone in the match can be chosen to host. While this is cheaper for the developers, it usually is not ideal for players.</p>
						<p>That’s not exactly a smooth gaming experience, especially on older hardware, as running both the game client and game server can be taxing.</p>
						<p>Both peer-to-peer and hosting from a home computer use one player’s home network.</p>
						<p>Which means everyone relies on home internet of the host.</p>
						<p>In peer-to-peer, the networking will attempt the best connection, but the host’s location can skew the ping to the advantage of certain players.</p>
						<p>Servers that are run from data centres have a lot of benefits over these two kinds of hosting.</p>
						<p>Most importantly: they are designed for and built with hosting multiplayer games in mind.</p>
						<p>The best experience for gamers is either dedicated servers from the developer or hosting their own dedicated server in a data centre. </p>
						<h2 class="mt-4">Why would you set up a private dedicated server?</h2>
						<p>While many gamers enjoy playing on public servers, there are several advantages to setting up a private server. Whether it is a local or remote server, running your own game server will have benefits. </p>
						<p>When you start your server setup process the first step is to choose what specific game you’re going to be hosting on the dedicated game server.</p>
						<p>Private server software means you can configure your game to have more control over who can join the game, moderation tools, and even mod support.</p>
						<p>Depending on what you’re playing, being the host of your own dedicated server means you can prevent players from interfering with your progress while you’re offline, or griefing other players.</p>
						<p>Whether choosing a server provider, using a separate PC to host locally, or running the dedicated server and game on the same computer, there is also increased control over the hardware in private dedicated servers.</p>
						<p>For example, if you need more memory for your dedicated server setup, that’s possible with many providers. If it is your own hardware, you can simply upgrade it.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">What type of hardware is in a game server?</h3>
						<p>Physically game servers are nothing but large racks of computer components.</p>
						<p>Like all servers, network switches connect them to the internet and the players.</p>
						<p>Unlike servers for less intensive applications, game servers are designed to handle the high workloads of hosting multiplayer with immense amounts of CPU power and RAM.</p>
