						<h2 class="mt-4">What is tick rate and how does it affect game servers?</h2>
						<p>A server‘s tick rate refers to how frequently updates to the game state are being broadcast back to the players.</p>
						<p>NEED A GRAPHIC</p>
						<p>A higher tick rate is more updates per second.</p>
						<p>Not all servers are the same, and not all games require the same kinds of servers.</p>
						<p>Turn-based games, like Hearthstone, don‘t need a high tick rate since the game does not update multiple times a second.</p>
						<p>Real-time games like DOTA, Counter-Strike, or Valorant do need higher tick rates to maintain synchronised game states.</p>
						<p>Games with real-time action will usually require higher tick rates for the best gameplay experience.</p>
						<h2 class="mt-4"><strong>Some sort of conclusion / synthesis</strong></h2>
						<h2 class="mt-4">Any other terms I should know about game servers?</h2>
						<p>There is no shortage of server terminology, here are some common words and phrases that will help you understand game servers.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">Uptime</h3>
						<p>Uptime is whether or not the server is accessible and connected to the internet. Servers will go ‘down’, generally due to either scheduled maintenance or a denial of service attack (DDoS).</p>
						<p>A server hosted on a home computer will also go down if the computer is turned off.</p>
						<p>Server providers may provide uptime guarantees, which is a <em>claim</em> that you will be able to gain access to the game server 99%, 99.9%, or 100% of the time. Effectively, the uptime guarantee keeps you in-game.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">Denial of service (DoS) attacks and distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks</h3>
						<p>Both of these malicious attacks are designed to prevent usage by overwhelming a server with illegitimate requests.</p>
						<p>DoS attacks focus on the endpoints rather than trying to disrupt a whole network, whereas DDoS attacks target the network as a whole.</p>
						<h3 class="mt-4">Game Client</h3>
						<p>Game clients is a fancy term for the game itself. If you’ve launched a game on your gaming PC or console, it is running the &quot;game client”.</p>
